The following code is meant to grab an element of a particular type out of a list, using implicit assignment in the if statement. Convert to LINQ separates the conditional body from the conditional assignment. Given this code:

```cs
interface IElement {}
List<IElement> list;
public T Get<T>() where T : IElement
{
    foreach (var el in list)
    {
        if (el is T t)
        {
            return t;
        }
    }
    return default;
}
```

This suggestion changes the function body to:

```cs
    foreach (var _ in from el in list
                      where el is T t
                      select new { })
    {
        return t;
    }
```

or the call form:

```cs
    foreach (var _ in list. Where(el => el is T t). Select(el => new { }))
    {
        return t;
    }
```

Neither of which is valid because they don't create the name 't' in the context for the return statement.

